 six months=E2=80=9D; things aren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0desperate=C2=A0yet, but PS=
TH is not exactly the freshest of SPACs. There was =E2=80=9Clots of specula=
tion that it would try to buy a company like Airbnb or Stripe, and word is =
that it did at least try to kick those sorts of tires,=E2=80=9D but I guess=
 that didn=E2=80=99t work out.Instead, Pershing Square announced a deal for=
 Universal Music Group. Uh, well, technically it announced that it=C2=A0mig=
ht=C2=A0have a deal: =E2=80=9CIt is in discussions with Vivendi S.E. (=E2=
=80=98Vivendi=E2=80=99) to acquire 10% of the outstanding Ordinary Shares o=
f Universal Music Group B.V. (=E2=80=98UMG=E2=80=99) for approximately $4 b=
illion, representing an enterprise value of =E2=82=AC35 billion for UMG.=E2=
=80=9D This is not a traditional SPAC deal, for a number of reasons. For on=
e thing, Universal is not a hot startup or a =E2=80=9Cmature unicorn,=E2=80=
=9D but a carveout from a public company.Also, though, the PSTH deal is not=
 a vehicle for=C2=A0taking Universal public: Vivendi was already planning t=
