<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><strong>Programming note:</strong> <em>I said =
yesterday that there would not be a Money Stuff=C2=A0today, but there will =
be. Here it is.</em></p><h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;=
Arial Black&quot;, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font=
-size: 20px; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; padding=
-bottom: 5px; margin-top: 30px; margin-bottom: 0;">SPARC SPARC SPARC</h2><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way a special purpose acquisition company wo=
rks is that investors put money in a pot, and the sponsor of the pot goes o=
ut and looks for a company to merge with. When the sponsor finds a target c=
ompany and does the=C2=A0merger, the target company gets the money in the p=
ot, and the investors in the pot get shares of the target company. (The spo=
nsor does too, as compensation for her target-hunting efforts.) Until then,=
 the pot is invested in money-market securities. If the sponsor doesn=E2=80=
=99t find a target company, or if the investors don=E2=80=99t like the merg=
er, they can get their money back with a tiny bit of interest.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you think too hard about this, it might seem a litt=
le inefficient. Why do the investors put the money in the pot at the=C2=A0<=
em>beginning</em>? It=E2=80=99s not doing anything. The money just sits the=
re. Why not wait until the sponsor finds a deal, and=C2=A0<em>then=C2=A0</e=
m>put the money in? While they wait for the sponsor to find a target, the S=
PAC investors can put their money into whatever they want, Treasury bills o=
r the S&amp;P 500 or AMC or Bitcoin or whatever. Then one day the sponsor s=
ays =E2=80=9Chere=E2=80=99s the deal,=E2=80=9D and the investors can decide=
 if they like it, and if they do they can give the sponsor their money and =
if they don=E2=80=99t they don=E2=80=99t have to. It=E2=80=99s the same bas=
ic economics as a SPAC =E2=80=94=C2=A0just like in a SPAC, the investors si=
gn up with a sponsor at the beginning not knowing what the deal is, but whe=
n the deal is announced they can decide whether or not they still want in =
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but without locking the money up in Treasury bills for month=
s or years.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you think too hard about=C2=
=A0<em>that</em>, you might say =E2=80=9Cwait that=E2=80=99s just an initia=
l public offering, the whole point of the SPAC is that you give money to th=
e sponsor first,=E2=80=9D but I don=E2=80=99t think that=E2=80=99s right. I=
n a SPAC you <em>do=C2=A0</em>give money to the sponsor first, but you can =
always get it back at the end. The money is <em>there</em>, but not <em>loc=
ked up</em>. Instead, the point of the SPAC is that you have expressed some=
 vote of confidence in the sponsor: You trust her to find you a good deal, =
so you sign up for her deal-finding expedition. You put up your money as an=
 expression of interest, not a commitment to invest. The point of the SPAC =
is not the money in the pool; the point of the SPAC is that a bunch of inve=
stors have expressed nonbinding interest in having a particular sponsor fin=
d a company for them. The valuable things are the sponsor=E2=80=99s connect=
ions and her curation and negotiation skills. If you have those things, rai=
sing the money later is fine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Pershing Squa=
re Tontine Holdings is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/c=
lick/24056212.282298/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLz=
E4MTE4ODIvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIxMTgxOTQyL2QxNzI3MjFkZXg5OTEuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cBaadacfe5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">doing lots of things</a>; here=E2=80=99s one of them:</p><blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">An affiliate of our Sponsor has formed an e=
ntity that will be known as Pershing Square SPARC Holdings, Ltd. (=E2=80=9C=
SPARC=E2=80=9D), which is a Cayman Islands Corporation.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">SPARC is not a SPAC. It is a Special Purpose Acquisition Right=
s Company. Unlike a traditional SPAC, SPARC does not intend to raise capita=
l through an underwritten offering in which investors commit capital withou=
t knowing the company with which SPARC will combine.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Instead, SPARC intends to issue rights to acquire common stock in=
 SPARC for $20.00 per share to PSTH shareholders (=E2=80=9CSPARs=E2=80=9D) =
which can only be exercised after SPARC enters into a definitive agreement =
for its initial business combination. The SPARs are expected to trade on th=
e NYSE and have a term of five years, subject to extension=E2=80=A6.</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Assuming all SPARs are exercised, SPARC will rais=
e $5.6 billion of cash from SPAR holders. SPARC is expected to enter into f=
orward purchase agreements with affiliates of the Pershing Square Funds, th=
e SPARC=E2=80=99s sponsor, for a minimum investment of $1 billion, and up t=
o $5 billion, subject to increase with SPARC=E2=80=99s board consent. ...</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SPARC=E2=80=99s structure has been designed =
to allow SPAR holders to avoid incurring the opportunity cost of capital of=
 a typical SPAC, as the SPARs will not be exercisable, and holders will not=
 be able to acquire shares in SPARC, until a definitive agreement has been =
signed. The SPARC Sponsor will also benefit by not having any time pressure=
 associated with the typical two-year SPAC commitment period.</p></blockquo=
te><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A SPARC is a SPAC without a pool of money. =
It doesn=E2=80=99t have shares; it has rights. You own a right =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0a SPAR =E2=80=94=C2=A0and you can trade that, and the sponsor of the SPA=
RC (Pershing Square Capital Management LP, Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s hedge fund=
) goes out and looks for a deal, and if it finds a good deal, it says =E2=
=80=9Chey who wants to put in $20 for this deal,=E2=80=9D and if you own a =
SPAR you can put in your $20 and get back a share of the deal. If you don=
=E2=80=99t own a SPAR, you can buy one from someone who does, and then put =
in your $20. If you do own a SPAR but don=E2=80=99t want in on the deal, yo=
u can sell your SPAR to someone who wants in.[1] The SPARs will, presumably=
, trade at some market price that reflects the market=E2=80=99s confidence =
that Bill Ackman will find and negotiate a good deal for the SPARC. If he a=
nnounces a deal and everyone hates it, then no one will want to put in $20 =
and the SPARs will trade to zero-ish. If he announces a deal and everyone l=
oves it, then investors will think, like, =E2=80=9CI can put in $20 and get=
 back $30 worth of stock in this awesome deal,=E2=80=9D and the SPARs will =
trade to $10-ish. Etc.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I like this? It is f=
un. It dispenses with almost all of the <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomb=
ergbusiness.com/click/24056212.282298/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZ=
XdzL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzLzIwMjEtMDEtMDgvbW9uZXktc3R1ZmYtc3BhYy1tYWdpYy1pc24tdC1m=
cmVl/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB3a21a69a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bord=
er-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: so=
lid; background-color: #ccc;">financial engineering</a> of a SPAC: There ar=
e no warrants, no cash value, no shareholder votes, no time limits. In fact=
 arguably there is no=C2=A0<em>anything.=C2=A0</em>Bill Ackman can go aroun=
d to private companies looking to go public and say =E2=80=A6=C2=A0what? =
=E2=80=9CHey, I=E2=80=99ve got some friends, and they are following with in=
terest my efforts to find a company to merge with. If I find a good one, ma=
ybe they=E2=80=99ll give me money, though they haven=E2=80=99t given me any=
 money yet and they=E2=80=99re under no obligation to do so. Would you like=
 to be that company, and maybe my friends will give you their money? We can=
 find out together!=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I want to emph=
asize that this really is the same pitch as a SPAC: In a SPAC, just like a =
SPARC, the sponsor cannot=C2=A0<em>guarantee=C2=A0</em>that any of the inve=
stors will actually contribute their money to the deal; SPAC investors have=
 withdrawal rights, while SPARC investors have no obligation to put in thei=
r money. (In a SPARC, just like a SPAC, the sponsor=C2=A0<em>itself=C2=A0</=
em>can put up some money to make the deal more certain for the target; here=
 Pershing Square will contribute between $1 billion and $5 billion to any d=
eal it finds.) The SPARC might feel a=C2=A0<em>bit=C2=A0</em>less real than=
 the SPAC, because the SPAC already has the money and the SPARC doesn=E2=80=
=99t, but I=E2=80=99m not sure that difference matters that much. The point=
 in either case is that=C2=A0a bunch of people want to invest with Bill Ack=
man, and have put their names on a nonbinding list that will let them do so=
.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But I also want to emphasize that this pi=
tch is also the same as =E2=80=A6 nothing? Like if Chamath Palihapitiya =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0or Bill Ackman for that matter =E2=80=94=C2=A0found some nice p=
rivate company and said =E2=80=9Chey, I would love to take you public, but =
all of my SPACs already did deals and I forgot to raise another one, what i=
f we just called all the people who like me and asked them to chip in some =
money,=E2=80=9D that would be=C2=A0<em>just as good as a SPARC</em>. There=
=E2=80=99s no pre-commitment here[2]; the pitch is not =E2=80=9CI have a po=
ol of money to give you=E2=80=9D but rather =E2=80=9Cpeople like me and tru=
st me and I probably=C2=A0<em>can=C2=A0</em>raise a pool of money for you.=
=E2=80=9D The SPARC formalizes that a little bit, but if you sign up to do =
a deal with Bill Ackman=E2=80=99s SPARC it=E2=80=99s not because the SPARC =
has money to give you, it=E2=80=99s because you are confident that Bill Ack=
man can=C2=A0<em>go find=C2=A0</em>money to give you.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Anyway, like I said, this is only one of the things that Pershin=
g Square Tontine Holdings is doing. PSTH is a SPAC (not a SPARC) that Bill =
Ackman launched=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/cli=
ck/24056212.282298/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE4=
MTE4ODIvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIwMTk3Nzc2L2Q5MzAwNTVkNDI0YjQuaHRt/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB0c60718b" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">way back in July 2020</a>; he raised $4 billion to <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24056212.282298/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjAtMDYtMjMvYmlsbC1hY2ttYW4td2FudH=
MtYS1tYXR1cmUtdW5pY29ybg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8ef4ec96" itemprop=3D"Sto=
ryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: n=
one !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bor=
der-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> hunt for</a> (in his wor=
ds) a =E2=80=9CMature Unicorn.=E2=80=9D PSTH did not find a Mature Unicorn.=
 PSTH is, however, a rather Mature SPAC at this point: Like all SPACs, it h=
as a two-year deadline to do a deal, and the clock started running last Jul=
y. That still gives it more than a year, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/24056212.282298/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xl=
cy9mb3Itc3RhcnR1cC1sZWFkZXJzLXNwYWNzLWhhdmUtbG9zdC10aGVpci1hbGx1cmUtMTE2MjE=
3NzQ4MDA_bW9kPWl0cF93c2omcnU9eWFob28/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB01fccbf7" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">but</a> =E2=
=80=9Cstartups tend to shy away from those that haven=E2=80=99t found a par=
tner after about six months=E2=80=9D; things aren=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>desper=
ate=C2=A0</em>yet, but PSTH is not exactly the freshest of SPACs. <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24056212.282298/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYXhpb3MuY29tL25ld3NsZXR0ZXJzL2F4aW9zLXByby1yYXRhLTUyNDQyNTVmLTUzZDMt=
NDYyNS04OGQxLTIxN2E2NTgyNTMzMy5odG1s/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbb203c94" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-d=
ecoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: =
#000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">There was</a>=
 =E2=80=9Clots of speculation that it would try to buy a company like Airbn=
b or Stripe, and word is that it did at least try to kick those sorts of ti=
res,=E2=80=9D but I guess that didn=E2=80=99t work out.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">Instead, Pershing Square announced a deal for Universal Music =
Group. Uh, well, technically <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/24056212.282298/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9k=
YXRhLzE4MTE4ODIvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTIxMTgxOTQzL2QxNzI3MjFkZXg5OTEuaHRt/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB432fd2e9" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">it announced that it=C2=A0<em>might=C2=A0</em>have a deal</a=
>: =E2=80=9CIt is in discussions with Vivendi S.E. (=E2=80=98Vivendi=E2=80=
=99) to acquire 10% of the outstanding Ordinary Shares of Universal Music G=
roup B.V. (=E2=80=98UMG=E2=80=99) for approximately $4 billion, representin=
g an enterprise value of =E2=82=AC35 billion for UMG.=E2=80=9D This is not =
a traditional SPAC deal, for a number of reasons. For one thing, Universal =
is not a hot startup or a =E2=80=9Cmature unicorn,=E2=80=9D but a carveout =
from a public company.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Also, though, the PS=
TH deal is not a vehicle for=C2=A0taking Universal public: Vivendi was alre=
ady <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24056212.28229=
8/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvZmZmNzA0OGItMWMwZC00NWE4LWFkNWItZmYyN=
zdkMzQwOTdm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB65423679" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" items=
cope=3D"itemscope" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">planning to spin off Universal</a> to =
its shareholders, and it will go ahead with that plan. Instead, PSTH will j=
ust buy some Universal shares from Vivendi; once Universal goes public (on =
Euronext Amsterdam) PSTH will distribute those shares to its own shareholde=
rs. The PSTH shares =E2=80=94=C2=A0which are listed on the New York Stock E=
xchange =E2=80=94=C2=A0won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>become=C2=A0</em>shares of th=
e newly public Universal; instead, PSTH shareholders will=C2=A0keep their P=
STH shares and also get some Universal shares as a distribution.</p><p styl=
e=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So PSTH will still exist and will still be publicly t=
raded on the New York Stock Exchange. It will also <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/24056212.282298/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi=
